7 COMMITTEE SUBSTITUTE
8 An Act relating to The Plumbing License Law of 1955;
amending 59 O.S. 2021, Sections 1003 and 1017, which
9 relate to definitions and inapplicability; defining
term; adding exceptions to applicability of certain
10 provisions; updating statutory language; updating
statutory reference; and providing an effective date.
11
12
13 BE IT ENACTED BY THE PEOPLE OF THE STATE OF OKLAHOMA:
14 SECTION 1. AMENDATORY 59 O.S. 2021, Section 1003, is
15 amended to read as follows:
16 Section 1003. As used in The Plumbing License Law of 1955:
17 1. “Board” means the Construction Industries Board;
18 2. “Committee” means the Oklahoma State Committee of Plumbing
19 Examiners appointed by the Construction Industries Board;
20 3. “Plumbing Hearing Board” means the State Plumbing Hearing
21 Board which shall consist of a designee of the Construction
22 Industries Board, as chair, and the members of the Oklahoma State
23 Committee of Plumbing Examiners;
24
Req. No. 3762 Page 1

1 4. “Apprentice” or “plumber’s apprentice” means any person
2 sixteen (16) years of age or older who, as the principal occupation
3 of the person, is engaged in learning and assisting in the
4 installation of plumbing under the direct supervision of a licensed
5 journeyman plumber or plumbing contractor;
6 5. “Journeyman plumber” means any person other than a master
7 plumber or plumbing contractor who engages in or works at the actual
8 installation, alteration, repair and/or, or renovation of plumbing;
9 6. “Temporary journeyman plumber” means any person other than a
10 person permanently licensed as a journeyman plumber, master plumber,
11 or plumbing contractor in this state who meets the temporary
12 licensure requirements of Section 1006.1 of this title;
13 7. “Master plumber” is a term used and defined under laws which
14 have been repealed. A person formerly known as a master plumber is
15 henceforth to be known as a “plumbing contractor” as defined in this
16 section;
17 8. “Plumbing contractor” means any person who is skilled in the
18 planning, superintending, and practical installation of plumbing and
19 who is familiar with the laws and rules governing the same. This
20 definition may be construed to mean any person who has qualified and
21 is licensed under The Plumbing License Law of 1955 as a plumbing
22 contractor, who may operate as an individual, a firm, partnership,
23 limited liability company, or corporation, or other legal entity to
24 engage in the business of plumbing, or the business of contracting
Req. No. 3762 Page 2

1 to d o plumbing, or furnish labor or materials or both for the
2 installation, repair, maintenance, or renovation of plumbing
3 according to the requirements of The Plumbing License Law of 1955.
4 Any former master plumber shall be known as a plumbing contractor;
5 9. 8. “Plumbing” means, and includes:
6 a. all piping, fixtures, appurtenances, and appliances
7 for, and in connection with, a supply of water within
8 or adjacent to any building, structure, or conveyance,
9 on the premises and to the connection with a water
10 main or other source of supply,
11 b. all piping, fixtures, appurtenances, and appliances
12 for sanitary drainage or storm drainage facilities,
13 including venting systems for such facilities, within
14 or adjacent to any building, structure, or conveyance,
15 on the premises and to the connection with a public
16 disposal system or other acceptable terminal,
17 c. the installation, repair, maintenance, and renovation
18 of all piping, fixtures, appurtenances, and appliances
19 for a supply of water, or for the disposal of waste
20 water, liquid waste, or sewage within or adjacent to
21 any building, structure, or conveyance, on the
22 premises and to the source of supply of water or point
23 of disposal of wastes, and
24
Req. No. 3762 Page 3

1 d. the installation, repair, and maintenance of radiant-
2 floor heating system piping in residential homes with
3 capacities no greater than one hundred thousand
4 (100,000) BTU’s BTUs using only piping approved by the
5 most current adopted edition of the International
6 Mechanical Code; and
7 9. “Utility contractor” means a corporation, partnership, or
8 sole proprietorship in good legal standing that specializes in the
9 construction, installation, maintenance, and repair of underground
10 infrastructure systems including water, sanitary sewer, storm or
11 drainage sewer, or gas, on behalf of a utility owner or the property
12 owner; and
13 10. “Variance and Appeals Board” means the Oklahoma State
14 Plumbing Installation Code Variance and Appeals Board.
15 SECTION 2. AMENDATORY 59 O.S. 2021, Section 1017, is
16 amended to read as follows:
17 Section 1017. The provisions of The Plumbing License Law of
18 1955 shall not apply to:
19 1. Minor repairs, consisting of repairing or replacing faucets
20 or minor working parts of plumbing fixtures;
21 2. Farm buildings located outside any city or town unless such
22 buildings are connected to a public water or sewer system;
23 3. Maintenance work for state institutions and school
24 districts;
Req. No. 3762 Page 4

1 4. The installation, maintenance, repair, renovation of
2 automatic sprinkler systems and related mechanical appurtenances
3 beginning at a point where the pipe or piping system provides water
4 used exclusively for these automatic sprinklers and their related
5 appurtenances and to standpipes connected to automatic sprinkler
6 systems;
7 5. The construction, installation, maintenance, repair,
8 renovation, and/or or removal of pipe or piping systems and related
9 mechanical appurtenances including backflow preventers, appliances
10 and/or or equipment used in connection therewith, directly or
11 indirectly within or without any building or structure, from a point
12 or location in a source of potable water supply at which point or
13 location there exists any backflow preventer, provided that said the
14 pipe and/or or piping systems are for:
15 a. heating, except radiant-floor heating systems as
16 defined provided for in subparagraph d of paragraph 9
17 8 of Section 1003 of this title,
18 b. cooling,
19 c. air conditioning,
20 d. refrigeration, or
21 e. boilers and other pressure vessels of whatsoever any
22 kind and character.
23 A “backflow preventer,”, as used herein in this paragraph, means
24 any permanent mechanical device, or combination of permanent
Req. No. 3762 Page 5

1 mech anical devices, of whatever any material, which, after
2 installation, acts to prevent a reversal of the normal directional
3 flow of potable water within the piping system in which it is
4 installed, and. Such term shall include, but not be limited to,
5 metal checkvalves check valves and airgaps air gaps, either
6 naturally or artificially created. Provided, further, that the
7 exclusionary provisions of this paragraph shall apply only to and
8 within governmental agencies, counties, cities, and towns which now
9 have or which hereafter may adopt separate laws relating to the
10 licensing, registration, and regulating of persons engaged, for
11 business purposes, in any of the areas of trade hereinbefore
12 specified in this paragraph; the. The exemptions herein being
13 provided to set forth in this paragraph shall apply only to these
14 items specifically regulated by any such local laws and ordinances;
15 and
16 6. An individual who performs plumbing work on such
17 individual’s property of residence; or
18 7. When the work is performed by a utility contractor who has a
19 Department of Environmental Quality Class D Operator certification:
20 a. plumbing work consisting of installing, servicing, or
21 repairing service mains, service lines, or sewer, gas,
22 or storm drainage services on private property in an
23 area that extends from a public right-of-way or public
24
Req. No. 3762 Page 6

1 easement to not less than five (5) feet from a
2 building or structure,
3 b. downspout boots, or
4 c. fire risers.
5 Work performed pursuant to paragraph 7 of this subsection shall
6 be done under the scope of the bond of the utility contractor and
7 shall not be done on repairs on previous work completed by a
8 plumbing contractor.
9 SECTION 3. This act shall become effective November 1, 2026.
